## 4. Offline Mode Explained

The alarm is designed to work completely without internet. Here is exactly what happens in each scenario:

| Scenario                              | Relay / Buzzer              | Blynk Dashboard                                     |
|---------------------------------------|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| WiFi connected, alarm ON              | Triggers on motion          | Notification + LED + label update                   |
| WiFi lost mid-session, alarm ON       | Still triggers on motion    | Dashboard shows device offline                      |
| No WiFi at all, alarm ON              | Still triggers on motion    | No update (no connection)                           |
| WiFi reconnects                       | Continues normally          | Alarm switch state restored via `syncVirtual(V2)`   |

> **How Offline Works in the Code**  
> The relay is driven by `setAlarmOutput()` which calls `digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, HIGH)` regardless of WiFi state. The `Blynk.virtualWrite()` calls are wrapped in `if (Blynk.connected())` checks so they are simply skipped when offline. The physical siren always works.

### WiFi Quick-Switch Logic

If the primary WiFi network is unavailable the ESP32 automatically tries the backup network within 8 seconds. Here is the sequence:

44. On boot (or after WiFi loss is detected), `tryConnect()` attempts `WIFI_SSID1` for 8 seconds.
45. If `WIFI_SSID1` fails, `tryConnect()` immediately attempts `WIFI_SSID2` for 8 seconds.
46. If both fail, the ESP runs in offline mode and checks again every 20 seconds.
47. The moment either network becomes available the ESP reconnects and Blynk resumes.

> **Tip: Set WIFI_SSID2 to Your Mobile Hotspot**  
> If your home router goes down you can enable your phone hotspot with the name and password set in `WIFI_SSID2`. The ESP32 will automatically connect to your phone within 8 seconds.

